Strategy 1: The Companion Local Backend (Highly Recommended)
Since you are already running this locally, the industry standard for this problem is to decouple the UI from the heavy processing by spinning up a lightweight local server. Python is significantly better at document processing than JavaScript.

The Architecture:

React Frontend sends the file path or streams the file to a local Python FastAPI or Node.js server.
The local server processes the file in chunks using system RAM (bypassing browser limits).
The server sends back the processed vector embeddings to the frontend's IndexedDB.
Best Libraries for this:

Python: unstructured (The gold standard for LLM document parsing). It handles PDF, DOCX, PPTX, and XLSX effortlessly.
Python: PyPDF2 or pdfplumber (for large PDFs).
Node.js (if you want to keep it JavaScript): pdf-parse (PDF), mammoth (DOCX), xlsx / SheetJS (Excel).
Strategy 2: Browser-Native Streaming & Garbage Collection (If you MUST stay 100% Frontend)
If you cannot add a backend and must process inside the React app, you cannot load the file as an ArrayBuffer all at once. You must implement Stream Processing and strict Garbage Collection.

1. Implement Origin Private File System (OPFS)
Instead of keeping the 50MB file in memory, write it directly to the browser's high-performance local virtual disk.

// OPFS allows you to stream large files without hitting RAM limits
const root = await navigator.storage.getDirectory();
const fileHandle = await root.getFileHandle('large_doc.pdf', { create: true });
// Stream chunks to disk directly
2. Page-by-Page PDF Processing
Your current implementation likely calls pdfjs.getDocument(), which loads the whole document structure into RAM. You must manually destroy objects page-by-page.

// Inside your Web Worker
const loadingTask = pdfjsLib.getDocument(fileData);
const pdf = await loadingTask.promise;

for (let i = 1; i <= pdf.numPages; i++) {
    const page = await pdf.getPage(i);
    const textContent = await page.getTextContent();
    
    // 1. Chunk the text
    // 2. Send chunk to Vector store/IndexedDB immediately
    
    // CRITICAL: Free up memory immediately
    page.cleanup(); 
}
// Destroy the main document when done
loadingTask.destroy(); 
3. Libraries for Office Files in the Browser
To support Office files in-browser without crashing, use these specialized libraries:

Excel/CSV: SheetJS (xlsx) or PapaParse. PapaParse is specifically designed to stream large CSV/Excel data row-by-row without loading the whole file into memory.
Word (.docx): mammoth.js. It ignores heavy formatting and only extracts raw text and semantic HTML, which uses a fraction of the memory.
PowerPoint (.pptx): docxtemplater or write a custom JS unzipper. (PPTX files are just ZIP files containing XML. You can use JSZip to stream the ZIP and only extract text from the slide[X].xml files, completely ignoring the heavy images).
Strategy 3: Wrap as a Local Desktop App (The "Tauri" Approach)
If your tool is meant to be run locally by your team, wrap your React/Vite app using Tauri (a lightweight alternative to Electron).

Why this fixes the problem immediately:

Tauri gives your React app access to a Rust-based backend automatically.
Rust can read a 50MB, 500MB, or 5GB file from the local file system using a buffer stream.
You don't need to load the file into the browser at all. Rust reads the file, chunks the text, and passes only the small 800-character chunks to your React frontend one by one via Tauri's IPC (Inter-Process Communication).
